Finance the introduction and mass production of very rapid-firing lever-action repeating rifles in the military. These weapons, Henry and Spencer Rifles, have been designed as recently as 1860. Their main advantage, the rapid rate of fire, is also the reason generals have their suspicions about these weapons. As the soldiers can consume their load of ammunition very rapidly, there are worries that the men would simply burn through the ammunition and then fall back, or some other similar folly.
Henry Rifles and Spencer Repeating Rifles and Carbines in production.


