Cavalry regiments are traditionally used by the army commanders for scouting, as messengers to relay orders, or to perform guard duties in the rear, in small detachments. Progressive cavalry officers are against this kind of dispersed use, and in favor of more independent cavalry use. This requires reforming organization, introducing cavalry brigades. Brigaded, the cavalry could support the army commander's operations more effectively, and even be able to stand their ground against infantry, if needed.\nThis project updates all existing cavalry units to brigades, and allows recruitment of cavalry brigades with up to 2500 troopers.
Cavalry Brigades available.
