Traditionally, American artillery batteries were comprised of four artillery pieces, two sections of two guns. During the Mexican War this usually was two cannons and two howitzers. To increase the firepower of field artillery batteries, introduce a new organization with six pieces and three sections. This is particularly useful when number of available guns is not severely limited. To simplify training and logistics, all guns in a battery are of same caliber.
